<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>HENDRICKSON SUSPENSION SYSTEMS - BUSHING REPLACEMENT - CENTER BUSHING REPLACEMENT RUBBER OR BRONZE (ON
        VEHICLE)
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="4">
        <title>CENTER BUSHING REPLACEMENT RUBBER OR BRONZE (ON VEHICLE)</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Remove</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Block front wheels.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Raise axles and support vehicle by the frame. Use frame stands.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>A jack must never be used alone to support vehicle while under-chassis service is being
                            per- formed. The jack may lower and serious personal injury could result. Always support
                            vehicle with floor stands.
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove wheels from the forward rear axle on the side that is being serviced. Refer to
                    Group 17-RIMS, WHEELS and TIRES in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the nuts/washers securing the saddle caps, then remove caps (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0300609">Figure 9</hotlnk>and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0300610">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0300609" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0300609" filename="../figg03/G0300609.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 9. Saddle Caps</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1.SADDLE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2.END PLUG</callout1>
                        <callout1>3.BEAM</callout1>
                        <callout1>4.SADDLE CAP</callout1>
                        <callout1>5.WASHER</callout1>
                        <callout1>6.SADDLE CAP STUD NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>7.EVEN GAP</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0300610" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0300610" filename="../figg03/G0300610.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10. Saddle Caps - Side View</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1.BEAM</callout1>
                        <callout1>2.SADDLE</callout1>
                        <callout1>3.CROSS TUBE</callout1>
                        <callout1>4.BEAM CENTER SLEEVE</callout1>
                        <callout1>5.THRUST WASHERS</callout1>
                        <callout1>6.LOCK NUTS</callout1>
                        <callout1>7.SADDLE CAP</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove bushings.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Use a hole saw to remove the plug that is welded on the outside end of the inner
                        section of the rubber bushing (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300611">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0300611" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300611" filename="../figg03/G0300611.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 11. End Plug</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.END PLUG</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Use a 2-inch (50.8-millimeter) diameter hole saw for 340 Series bushings; use a 2-1/2
                                inch (63.5 millimeter) diameter hole saw for 380 through 450 Series bushings.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <para>For bronze bushings, remove center sleeve by hand (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0300612">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0300612" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0300612" filename="../figg03/G0300612.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 12. Center Sleeve</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.LUBE HOLES</callout1>
                            <callout1>2.BUSHING LUBE GROOVES (THESE MUST LAY ALONG THE CENTERLINE, AS SHOWN)</callout1>
                            <callout1>3.LUBE FITTING</callout1>
                            <callout1>4.CENTER BUSHING ASSEMBLY (CENTER IN HUB AS SHOWN)</callout1>
                            <callout1>5.CENTERLINE OF BEAM</callout1>
                            <callout1>6.DO NOT BEND SEAL</callout1>
                            <callout1>7.1/16 INCH +/- 1/32 (1.6 MM +/- 0.8)</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After the plug has been cut out or the center sleeve removed, remove the cross tube
                    through the hole.
                </para>
                <para>With bronze bushings, remove the seal on the bushing side of the beam.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a special tool (hydraulic press) per tool instructions, remove center bushing from
                    beam. Refer to SPECIAL TOOLS,
                    <hotlnk document="s03006s_30.xml" xrefid="f0300644">Figure 44</hotlnk>,
                    <hotlnk document="s03006s_30.xml" xrefid="f0300645">Figure 45</hotlnk>, and
                    <hotlnk document="s03006s_30.xml" xrefid="f0300646">Figure 46</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Install</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Do not install BRONZE CENTER BUSHINGS into aluminum suspension beams.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Do not install BRONZE CENTER BUSHINGS into U/UE Series suspensions.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After removing the bushings, thoroughly inspect the beam bores.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>If torch undercutting is found from previous maintenance procedures, replace the beam. Do
                            not take responsibility for possible road failure by rebushing a defective beam.
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the beam center bores with emery cloth, removing any nicks or metal build-up.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use emery cloth to remove the rust-protective coating from the outer metal of the new
                    bushing, then apply a thin coat of multi-purpose grease.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using the special tool, per tool instructions install new bushing into beam.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lubricate both ends of the cross tube and install tube.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install bushing Plug/Center.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">With rubber bushing, install bushing plug in the same location as the one removed,
                        and arc weld in place.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">With bronze bushing, install thrust washer/seal on center sleeve.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a jack, raise beam into position. Install saddle caps and washers/nuts, then
                    tighten to specifications. Refer to the
                    <hotlnk document="s03006s_29.xml" xrefid="hl0300604">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>. Remove jack from beam.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install wheels, refer to GROUP 17-RIMS, WHEELS AND TIRES in the CTS-5000 Master Service
                    Manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lower vehicle and put back into service.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
